<dl id="n03062g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03062g">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03062g"> 62(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ &mdash; broth &mdash; <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03062g"><li>FW 211.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/h/lexh.htm#n03062g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/h/l39h.htm#n03062g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03062g">MS BL 47474-134v</ms> </li><li>JJA 48:070 I.8&sect;1A.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The little crowd were at hand. The old man stepped outside the wicket and the opening was a narrow one and he stood helplessly by, bent down like the bough of an ancient tree.&ldquo;Michael,&rdquo; he said to Michael Keohane, who, he knew, was captain over them; &ldquo;ah, Michael, he&apos;s only a boy, a slip of a boy.&rdquo; But Keohane, who for the past few years had had always more problems to decide upon than he was able to come at, had acquired a quick and somewhat hard way of answering such questions as took one no further. <small> Daniel Corkery, <a name="DCHB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#DCHB"><cite title="source">The Hounds of Banba</cite></a> (1920) 200</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <i>Slip</i> can mean a young person of either sex, esp. one of small and slender build, as well as &ldquo;a soft semi-lquid mass&rdquo; or &ldquo;curdled milk&rdquo; (OED). Maybe this occasioned Joyce&apos;s variation &ldquo;broth&rdquo;. (RJH) </mm> </dd></dl>
